body: This sounds like it's finding the stub \windows\system32\onnxruntime.dll vs the one installed through nuget. Is there a way to be sure the onnxruntime.dll is on the path when running the app?

Do you mean like this?

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2119539/how-do-i-set-the-path-to-a-dll-file-in-visual-studio

but this is a little old and I am not entirely sure which lib i should reference and how to perform this... note here is the full error

Well I do get this error even though I use onnxruntime in the startup project only (ASP.NET MVC5). Tried versions 1.2.1, 1.8.1, 1.10.0. All fail. My test WPF project in .NET 5 works.

From the loader:
`Loaded 'C:\Users\xxxxx\AppData\Local\Temp\Temporary ASP.NET Files\vs\8ead1128\c79b5550\assembly\dl3\9fa905b5\00b98840_1debd701\Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.dll'. Symbols loaded.`

This is still a problem and can be reproduced with a simple console app and a reference to the Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime package.   It will load the version on system32 rather than the one from the package.  We have seen reports of this from multiple customers of ML.NET.  Could you reopen this bug and consider a fix?

The issue for me was seen in .NET 6 environment, specifically dotnet/interactive environment (Note: I did not see the same from my visual studio 2022 Console project environment)

I was able to workaround it in the dotnet/interactive environment by using the workaround steps provided via:
https://github.com/dotnet/interactive/issues/967#issuecomment-868738762

The only change I had to make was switch the part that said
```csharp
 @"microsoft.ml.onnxruntime/1.6.0/runtimes/"
```
to my current version of  Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime, <current_version>

```csharp
 @"microsoft.ml.onnxruntime/<current_version>/runtimes/"
```

I also have this problem, my workaround is to build two separate DLLs, one for 32-bit and one for 64-bit. If I build an AnyCPU DLL and load it in a 32-bit app, then i get the above error. I don't understand DLL loading nearly well enough to understand what's happening here - but my guess is that it's something to do with the onnxruntime DLL deployed with nuget being picked up if you try and run 32-bit without explicitly building a 32-bit version?
This is till unfixed, how come this issue is closed??

I just installed "Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime"  and works property. My environment was .NET 6 and I was having the same problem, so it is possible that they are forgetting to install this package. If you have it installed and are getting the same exception then it is a deeper problem.
